Programming Assignment 1: Basic Indexing and Querying

Hosted Website:
	http://search.jonjrodriguez.com
	indexed example zipped directory

Languages/Versions Used:
	Python 2.7.11
	PyLucene 4.10.1

File Structure:
	src/: the index, code for indexer, and code for retriever
	Lucene/: code of configured and compile PyLucene for Mac OSX 10.11
	HTMLParser/: code for html parser (beautifulsoup4)
	web/: code for web page
	docs/: default location to store html files for indexing
	run.py: utility file to easily run commands {index,search,serve}

Dependencies:
	BeautifulSoup (HTML Parser):
	http://www.crummy.com/software/BeautifulSoup/

	Flask (Web Microframework):
	http://flask.pocoo.org/

Setup:
	1. Build PyLucene on your system (located in Lucene and configured for Mac OSX 10.11)
		https://lucene.apache.org/pylucene/install.html

	2. Install BeautifulSoup
		http://www.crummy.com/software/BeautifulSoup/bs4/doc/#installing-beautiful-soup

		Quick instructions:
			- pip install beautifulsoup4
				OR
			- cd HTMLParser
			- python setup.py install

	3. Install flask
		http://flask.pocoo.org/docs/0.10/installation/#installation

		Quick instructions:
			- pip install flask

Usage:
	1. Using default options
		python run.py {index, search, serve}

		index:
			Indexes any html files (.html or .htm extension) located in the docs folder
			Index will be store in src/index

		search:
			Will search index stored in src/index
			Command line will prompt you for your search query

		serve:
			Will launch local web server
			Visit http://127.0.0.1:5000/ in browser

	2. Using command line options (from src directory)

		index:
		python indexer.py [-index INDEX_PATH] [-docs DOCS_PATH]
	
		optional arguments:
	  	-index INDEX_PATH  The relative path where the index will be stored (default: index)
	  	-docs DOCS_PATH    The relative path where the documents are stored (default: ../docs)

  		search:
  		python retriever.py [-index INDEX_PATH] QUERY

		positional arguments:
		  QUERY              The query to use to search the index

		optional arguments:
		  -index INDEX_PATH  The relative path where the index is stored (default: index)
